postcontent:
For sale from my dads collection is this Mossberg Brownie Four-Barrel .22 Short Derringer in good condition, no damage of any kind, it is missing the ejector rod which is common for these Four-Barrel .22 Short Derringers. A part that is not really needed, this part could be easily fabricated by someone with metal skills, a simple part to make, it should be 3/8" wide, 1/16" thick and 3 & 5/8" long, used to push the fired casings out of the barrels, it fits into a small slot in the handle. 

This is a solid gun, approximately 4 & 7/8" long, 3 & 1/4" wide, 3/4" thick with a total weight of 1 pound 1.8 ounces empty. 

Patented July 27, 1920, this was a favorite pocket pistol during the roaring 20's for both the men and the ladies during those wild times, easy to use with a double action rotating firing pin.

It is from my dad's collection and has not been fired for a very long time but it still functions perfectly. It could use a good cleaning.

title: For Sale:  Safe Transactions
postcontent: As we all know, there are quite a lot of scams floating around here. I have stumbled across several, and found that the best way to assure that a deal is legitimate is to contact a gun shop in the area of the seller. Most are very happy to deal with the transfer (if it's a modern gun, an FFL dealer is required to do so), and the few I've worked with charged $25 for the transfer plus actual shipping. I had the seller bring the gun to the shop and once they had it and confirmed to me that it was as advertised, I sent the shop two certified checks, one for their fees and the second to the seller. He picked his check up from them and the item was shipped. Safe for everyone, legal, and sensible. If a seller won't do it that way, they're probably a fraud. Good luck.
